Title: The Wee Free Men (Discworld, #30; Tiffany Aching, #1)
Author: Terry Pratchett
My Review:
Miss Tick sniffed. “You could say this advice is priceless,” she said, “Are you listening?”
“Yes,” said Tiffany.
“Good. Now...if you trust in yourself...”
“Yes?”
“...and believe in your dreams...”
“Yes?”
“...and follow your star...” Miss Tick went on.
“Yes?”
“...you’ll still be beaten by people who spent their time working hard and learning things and weren’t so lazy. Goodbye.”

Title: The Game-Players of Titan
Author: Philip K. Dick
My Review: Gambling addicted aliens have taken over the earth. Our hero must fight them along with his trusty sidekick, a depressed auto auto. He is helped by shape shifting entities who may or may not be aliens, may or may not be helping him and may or may not be reading minds.

Title: गोदान
Author: Munshi Premchand
My Review:
Books with Social realism date badly. Most books from just 20 years ago look anachronistic because society and expectations from relationships change. गोदान and most stories from Premchand is not one.

गोदान cuts to the core of human emotions and does it with compassion and wit. It is set in a rural village in India but if you lived in cities all your life and never set foot in India, you can still empathise with the characters.

Title: House Atreides (Prelude to Dune, #1)
Author: Brian Herbert
My Review:
(This a review of all books Brian H. wrote in Dune world, not just the Prelude to Dune #1)

Frank Herbert took 5 novels to create the magical world of Dune. Brian H. destroys that magic in just one book.

One of the most enjoyable things about Dune is that all factions/entities have shades of grey and plans within their plan. Brian H. books change them to a linear narrative and put entities in a black/white divide. This is infuriating, and entirely at odds with the world Frank H. built.

Eg. In the original books even Tleilaxu are not evil. Loathsome and power hungry, yes. But not evil. They are chaotic-neutral. There are no real antagonists, except humanity's shared past and the uncertain future.
In Herbert/Anderson books they turn into slave traders and organ harvesters.

If you love Dune series for its complexity and heroes of uncertain morality, stay away.

My Review: A worthy successor to Dune. Drag a little in parts, but is needed for the story which comes in later books.

Title: A Game of Thrones (A Song of Ice and Fire, #1)
Author: George R.R. Martin
My Review:
(This is a review of all ASOIF books, not just the #1).
As an young boy I read LOTR. It hooked me to the high fantasy genre.

I read LOTR multiple times. For years I couldn’t stop thinking about it. I started writing fan fiction about it. I read WoT, Mazlan Book, SoT, but they all came short. I was left seeking the first thrill.

And then I found ASOIAF. I threw down the book when Ned dies. I vowed to never come back after the red wedding. I had to take a break when Arya goes blind.

It’s easy to kill off characters. It is hard to make readers empathise when they die.
